,\\\"addressCountry\\\":\\\"IN\\\",\\\"addressRegion\\\":\\\"Andhra Pradesh\\\"}}},{\\\"@context\\\":\\\"https://schema.org\\\",\\\"@type\\\":\\\"FAQPage\\\",\\\"mainEntity\\\":[{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"Question\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"Can a dirty helmet cause acne?\\\",\\\"acceptedAnswer\\\":{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"Answer\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"Yes. Sweat, friction, and bacteria trapped inside the helmet can cause acne on the forehead, cheeks, and even the scalp.\\\"}},{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"Question\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"Does wearing a dirty helmet increase dandruff or hair fall?\\\",\\\"acceptedAnswer\\\":{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"Answer\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"It can contribute to dandruff, scalp irritation, and temporary hair shedding due to fungal growth and clogged hair follicles.\\\"}},{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"Question\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"How can I prevent skin and hair problems from my helmet?\\\",\\\"acceptedAnswer\\\":{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"Answer\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"Regular deep sanitization of your helmet, especially using dry UV-C and ozone methods, helps eliminate harmful microbes and protect scalp health.\\\"}}]}]\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"14:[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"script\\\",null,{\\\"type\\\":\\\"application/ld+json\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"$1c\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L1d\\\",null,{\\\"post\\\":{\\\"slug\\\":\\\"how-dirty-helmets-can-affect-your-skin-and-hair-health\\\",\\\"title\\\":\\\"How Dirty Helmets Can Affect Your Skin and Hair Health\\\",\\\"banner\\\":\\\"/images/banners/dirty-helmet-skin-hair-effects.jpg\\\",\\\"headline\\\":\\\"Let’s Talk About What Your Helmet Might Be Doing to Your Skin and Hair\\\",\\\"description\\\":\\\"You may not realize it, but a dirty helmet can cause acne, dandruff, scalp irritation, and even hair problems. Let’s understand in simple terms how it happens and how you can prevent it.\\\",\\\"publishedAt\\\":\\\"2025-05-21\\\",\\\"author\\\":\\\"Freshpod Editorial\\\",\\\"tags\\\":[\\\"helmet hygiene\\\",\\\"scalp acne\\\",\\\"dandruff helmet\\\",\\\"folliculitis riders\\\",\\\"hair health helmet\\\",\\\"skin infections helmet\\\",\\\"FreshPod\\\",\\\"helmet\\\",\\\"bacteria\\\",\\\"virus\\\"],\\\"order\\\":[\\\"hero-text\\\",\\\"section-sweat-trap\\\",\\\"image-scalp-irritation\\\",\\\"section-skin-problems\\\",\\\"section-hair-issues\\\",\\\"section-why-it-happens\\\",\\\"section-freshpod-prevention\\\",\\\"cta-contact\\\"],\\\"content\\\":{\\\"hero-text\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"text\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"Your helmet is meant to protect your head from injury. But if it is not cleaned properly, it can slowly affect your skin and hair. After every ride, sweat, oil from your scalp, dead skin cells, and dust get trapped inside the helmet padding. Over time, this creates a warm and moist space where bacteria and fungi grow easily. Many riders blame stress or \\\\\\\"helmet hair\\\\\\\" for their scalp problems, but often the real reason is poor helmet hygiene.\\\"},\\\"section-sweat-trap\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"How Sweat and Dirt Build Up Inside\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"When you ride in hot weather, your head sweats a lot. That sweat gets absorbed into the helmet liner. It mixes with natural oils (called sebum), dirt from the road, and tiny microbes already present on your skin. This combination creates the perfect environment for bacteria and fungi to multiply. Each time you wear the same unclean helmet, those germs come back into contact with your scalp and face.\\\"},\\\"image-scalp-irritation\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"image\\\",\\\"src\\\":\\\"/images/banners/scalp-irritation-helmet.png\\\",\\\"alt\\\":\\\"Close-up view of scalp irritation and acne caused by dirty helmet use\\\",\\\"caption\\\":\\\"Redness, pimples, and dandruff are common signs of poor helmet hygiene.\\\"},\\\"section-skin-problems\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"Common Skin Problems Riders Face\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"One common issue is acne mechanica, which appears as small red pimples where the helmet presses against your forehead or cheeks. Dirty padding makes this worse because it contains acne-causing bacteria. Riders may also experience folliculitis, which looks like small painful bumps around hair follicles. Other problems include seborrheic dermatitis (itchy, flaky patches) and fungal infections. If helmets are shared, these skin issues can spread from one person to another.\\\"},\\\"section-hair-issues\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"How It Affects Your Hair\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"Excess moisture and fungal growth can increase dandruff and scalp irritation. When hair follicles stay clogged and inflamed, hair roots can weaken. This may lead to hair breakage, thinning, or temporary shedding. Helmets do not cause genetic baldness, but wearing a dirty helmet regularly can make your hair look unhealthy, dull, and damaged over time.\\\"},\\\"section-why-it-happens\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"Why These Problems Keep Happening\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"Many riders only wipe the outside of their helmet or use surface sprays. These methods clean what you can see but do not deeply sanitize the inner padding. Washing with water can sometimes leave moisture behind, which encourages more microbial growth if not dried properly. Because germs are invisible, people often ignore the issue until irritation becomes serious.\\\"},\\\"section-freshpod-prevention\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"How FreshPod Helps Protect Your Skin and Hair\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"FreshPod provides a simple and effective solution. It uses UV-C light and ozone technology to kill 99.9% of bacteria, viruses, and fungi in just 3–5 minutes. The process is completely dry, meaning there is no added moisture and no chemical damage to helmet materials. By regularly sanitizing your helmet, you reduce the risk of skin infections, dandruff, and scalp irritation — helping keep both your skin and hair healthy.\\\"},\\\"cta-contact\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"cta\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"Take Care of Your Helmet — Take Care of Yourself\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"Keeping your helmet clean is not just about smell; it is about protecting your skin and hair. Start maintaining proper helmet hygiene today.\\\",\\\"label\\\":\\\"Get in Touch Now\\\",\\\"href\\\":\\\"/#contact\\\"}},\\\"seo\\\":{\\\"metaTitle\\\":\\\"How Dirty Helmets Affect Skin and Hair Health\\\",\\\"metaDescription\\\":\\\"Learn how unclean helmets can cause acne, dandruff, scalp irritation, and hair problems. Discover how proper helmet sanitization helps protect skin and hair health.\\\",\\\"keywords\\\":[\\\"dirty helmet skin\\\",\\\"helmet acne\\\",\\\"scalp dandruff helmet\\\",\\\"folliculitis helmet\\\",\\\"hair thinning helmet\\\",\\\"seborrheic dermatitis riders\\\",\\\"scalp infections helmet\\\",\\\"helmet hygiene\\\",\\\"bacteria in helmet\\\"],\\\"ogImage\\\":\\\"/images/dirty-helmet-skin-hair-effects.jpg\\\",\\\"canonicalUrl\\\":\\\"https://freshpod.in/blog/how-dirty-helmets-can-affect-your-skin-and-hair-health\\\",\\\"schemaType\\\":\\\"BlogPosting\\\",\\\"aeo\\\":{\\\"faqItems\\\":[{\\\"q\\\":\\\"Can a dirty helmet cause acne?\\\",\\\"a\\\":\\\"Yes. Sweat, friction, and bacteria trapped inside the helmet can cause acne on the forehead, cheeks, and even the scalp.\\\"},{\\\"q\\\":\\\"Does wearing a dirty helmet increase dandruff or hair fall?\\\",\\\"a\\\":\\\"It can contribute to dandruff, scalp irritation, and temporary hair shedding due to fungal growth and clogged hair follicles.\\\"},{\\\"q\\\":\\\"How can I prevent skin and hair problems from my helmet?\\\",\\\"a\\\":\\\"Regular deep sanitization of your helmet, especially using dry UV-C and ozone methods, helps eliminate harmful microbes and protect scalp health.\\\"}]},\\\"geo\\\":{\\\"locality\\\":\\\"India\\\",\\\"region\\\":\\\"Andhra Pradesh\\\",\\\"country\\\":\\\"India\\\"}}},\\\"prevPost\\\":{\\\"slug\\\":\\\"hidden-germs-inside-your-helmet-you-never-knew-about\\\",\\\"title\\\":\\\"Hidden Germs Inside Your Helmet You Never Knew About\\\",\\\"banner\\\":\\\"/images/banners/hidden-helmet-germs.jpg\\\",\\\"headline\\\":\\\"Let Me Tell You What’s Really Hiding Inside Your Helmet\\\",\\\"description\\\":\\\"Most riders clean the outside of their helmet but forget what’s happening inside. Let’s break down, in simple words, the bacteria and fungi that grow in helmet padding and why proper sanitization matters.\\\",\\\"publishedAt\\\":\\\"2025-05-18\\\",\\\"author\\\":\\\"Freshpod Editorial\\\",\\\"tags\\\":[\\\"helmet bacteria\\\",\\\"hidden germs\\\",\\\"helmet fungi\\\",\\\"rider hygiene\\\",\\\"FreshPod sanitization\\\"],\\\"order\\\":[\\\"hero-text\\\",\\\"section-scientific-evidence\\\",\\\"image-microbes\\\",\\\"section-common-pathogens\\\",\\\"section-health-consequences\\\",\\\"section-why-most-riders-miss-this\\\",\\\"section-freshpod-eliminates\\\",\\\"cta-contact\\\"],\\\"content\\\":{\\\"hero-text\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"text\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"Let me explain something that most riders don’t realize. You may wipe the outside of your helmet after a dusty ride and feel satisfied. But the real problem is not outside — it is inside the padding. The inside of a helmet is warm, dark, and full of sweat after every ride. That is the perfect place for tiny germs to grow. Scientific studies have actually tested used helmets and found surprising amounts of bacteria and fungi living inside them.\\\"},\\\"section-scientific-evidence\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"What Scientists Found Inside Real Helmets\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"In one detailed study, researchers examined 130 used motorcycle helmets. They found hundreds of different bacterial and fungal samples inside them. On average, each helmet had multiple types of microbes growing in the padding. The reason is simple: sweat, heat, and poor ventilation create an ideal environment for germs. When a helmet is worn daily and not deeply cleaned, it slowly becomes like a small laboratory for bacteria.\\\"},\\\"image-microbes\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"image\\\",\\\"src\\\":\\\"/images/banners/helmet-microbial-growth.png\\\",\\\"alt\\\":\\\"Microscopic view of bacteria and fungi growing inside helmet padding\\\",\\\"caption\\\":\\\"Scientific testing shows multiple bacteria and fungi can live inside uncleaned helmet interiors.\\\"},\\\"section-common-pathogens\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"Common Germs Found in Helmets\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"Some of the bacteria commonly found include Staphylococcus aureus, Staphylococcus epidermidis, Escherichia coli (E. coli), Pseudomonas aeruginosa, and Bacillus species. Some strains of Staphylococcus can even be resistant to certain antibiotics. On the fungal side, researchers often find Aspergillus species, Candida, Rhizopus, and Penicillium. Many of these organisms normally live in the environment, but in warm and moist conditions, they can multiply quickly and cause infections.\\\"},\\\"section-health-consequences\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"How These Germs Can Affect You\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"At first, you may only notice a bad smell from your helmet. Then you might experience an itchy scalp, dandruff, small painful bumps, or pimples around your forehead. In some cases, riders develop folliculitis (infected hair follicles), fungal scalp infections, or skin irritation. If helmets are shared — like in delivery fleets or rental services — there is also a risk of passing germs from one person to another.\\\"},\\\"section-why-most-riders-miss-this\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"Why Most Riders Don’t Realize the Problem\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"The inside padding of a helmet is not always easy to clean deeply. Surface sprays and wipes only clean what you can see. Sun drying may reduce moisture but does not fully kill strong bacteria or fungi. Washing with water can sometimes damage helmet foam if not done properly. Because germs are invisible, most riders do not think about them until there is a strong smell or skin irritation.\\\"},\\\"section-freshpod-eliminates\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"How FreshPod Helps Solve This Problem\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"FreshPod is designed to clean helmets properly from the inside. It uses UV-C light and ozone to destroy 99.9% of bacteria and fungi in just 3–5 minutes. The process is dry, meaning no water and no chemicals are used. This helps protect the helmet padding and foam while making sure germs are eliminated. Instead of guessing whether your helmet is clean, you can be confident it is sanitized safely and effectively.\\\"},\\\"cta-contact\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"cta\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"Protect Yourself from Hidden Helmet Germs\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"Now that you know what can grow inside your helmet, it makes sense to take proper action. Keeping your helmet clean means protecting your health.\\\",\\\"label\\\":\\\"Contact FreshPod Team\\\",\\\"href\\\":\\\"/#contact\\\"}},\\\"seo\\\":{\\\"metaTitle\\\":\\\"Hidden Germs Inside Your Helmet | What’s Really Growing There\\\",\\\"metaDescription\\\":\\\"Discover the bacteria and fungi commonly found inside uncleaned motorcycle helmets and understand the health risks. Learn how proper sanitization keeps riders safe.\\\",\\\"keywords\\\":[\\\"hidden germs helmet\\\",\\\"helmet bacteria\\\",\\\"motorcycle helmet fungi\\\",\\\"Staphylococcus in helmets\\\",\\\"Aspergillus helmet\\\",\\\"helmet padding germs\\\",\\\"helmet sanitization\\\"],\\\"ogImage\\\":\\\"/images/banners/hidden-helmet-germs.jpg\\\",\\\"canonicalUrl\\\":\\\"https://freshpod.in/blog/hidden-germs-inside-your-helmet-you-never-knew-about\\\",\\\"schemaType\\\":\\\"BlogPosting\\\",\\\"aeo\\\":{\\\"faqItems\\\":[{\\\"q\\\":\\\"What bacteria are commonly found inside motorcycle helmets?\\\",\\\"a\\\":\\\"Common bacteria include Staphylococcus aureus, Staphylococcus epidermidis, E. coli, Pseudomonas aeruginosa, and Bacillus species, along with fungi such as Aspergillus and Candida.\\\"},{\\\"q\\\":\\\"Can helmet germs cause health problems?\\\",\\\"a\\\":\\\"Yes. They can cause bad odor, scalp infections, folliculitis, fungal issues, acne, and irritation. Shared helmets may also spread germs between users.\\\"},{\\\"q\\\":\\\"How can I properly sanitize my helmet?\\\",\\\"a\\\":\\\"Deep sanitization methods such as UV-C and ozone-based systems help eliminate bacteria and fungi effectively without damaging helmet materials.\\\"}]},\\\"geo\\\":{\\\"locality\\\":\\\"India\\\",\\\"region\\\":\\\"Andhra Pradesh\\\",\\\"country\\\":\\\"India\\\"}}},\\\"nextPost\\\":{\\\"slug\\\":\\\"the-science-behind-helmet-bacteria-growth\\\",\\\"title\\\":\\\"The Science Behind Helmet Bacteria Growth\\\",\\\"banner\\\":\\\"/images/banners/helmet-bacteria-science.jpg\\\",\\\"headline\\\":\\\"Let’s Understand How Your Helmet Becomes a Germ Breeding Ground\\\",\\\"description\\\":\\\"Ever wondered why bacteria grow so fast inside helmets? Let’s break down the simple science behind sweat, heat, and moisture — and how proper sanitization stops the cycle.\\\",\\\"publishedAt\\\":\\\"2025-05-24\\\",\\\"author\\\":\\\"Freshpod Editorial\\\",\\\"tags\\\":[\\\"helmet bacteria growth\\\",\\\"microbial science helmet\\\",\\\"sweat bacteria helmet\\\",\\\"fungi helmet padding\\\",\\\"helmet hygiene science\\\",\\\"FreshPod\\\",\\\"helmet\\\",\\\"bacteria\\\",\\\"virus\\\"],\\\"order\\\":[\\\"hero-text\\\",\\\"section-basic-microbial-growth\\\",\\\"image-growth-factors\\\",\\\"section-helmet-environment\\\",\\\"section-key-factors-explained\\\",\\\"section-real-study-evidence\\\",\\\"section-how-freshpod-interrupts\\\",\\\"cta-contact\\\"],\\\"content\\\":{\\\"hero-text\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"text\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"On the outside, your helmet looks like a simple safety tool. But inside, it becomes a small environment of its own. After every ride, sweat, tiny skin particles, natural oils, and dust collect inside the padding. In warm climates where temperatures reach 30–40°C, this creates the perfect condition for bacteria and fungi to grow quickly. What seems harmless at first can turn into heavy microbial growth within just a few days.\\\"},\\\"section-basic-microbial-growth\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"How Bacteria Multiply So Fast\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"Bacteria reproduce through a process called binary fission. This means one bacterium splits into two. Under ideal conditions, this can happen every 20–30 minutes. Because of this rapid division, one single bacterium can grow into thousands or even millions within hours. Fungi spread through spores and grow in thread-like structures in moist areas. For microbes to grow, they need four main things: food (like sweat and dead skin), water (moisture), the right temperature (usually 25–40°C), and time. Helmets provide all of these.\\\"},\\\"image-growth-factors\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"image\\\",\\\"src\\\":\\\"/images/banners/bacteria-growth-diagram-helmet.jpg\\\",\\\"alt\\\":\\\"Diagram showing exponential bacterial growth in warm and moist helmet interior\\\",\\\"caption\\\":\\\"Warm temperature, moisture, nutrients, and time together cause rapid microbial growth inside helmets.\\\"},\\\"section-helmet-environment\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"Why Helmet Interiors Are Ideal for Germ Growth\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"The inside of a helmet is dark and enclosed. It traps body heat and limits airflow. Sweat soaks into soft foam and fabric, providing both moisture and nutrients. The internal temperature during a ride often stays within the ideal range for common bacteria. When helmets are used daily without proper sanitization, microbes continue multiplying. Shared helmets make this worse because different users introduce new bacteria each time.\\\"},\\\"section-key-factors-explained\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"The Main Scientific Factors That Help Germs Grow\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"Temperature: Most helmet bacteria grow best between 25–40°C. Moisture: Sweat increases humidity inside the helmet, which microbes need. Nutrients: Proteins and oils from sweat act as food. pH Level: Slight acidity from sweat supports skin-related bacteria. Time: If a helmet is not disinfected regularly, bacteria keep multiplying day after day. Studies show that helmets used for years without deep cleaning have much higher microbial contamination.\\\"},\\\"section-real-study-evidence\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"What Research on Real Helmets Shows\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"Scientific studies on used motorcycle helmets have found high levels of bacteria and fungi. Common bacteria include Staphylococcus aureus, Staphylococcus epidermidis, Escherichia coli, and Pseudomonas aeruginosa. Fungi such as Aspergillus and Candida are also frequently detected. Research shows that helmets that are rarely cleaned have significantly higher contamination levels compared to those that are maintained properly.\\\"},\\\"section-how-freshpod-interrupts\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"section\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"How FreshPod Stops the Growth Cycle\\\",\\\"body\\\":\\\"FreshPod uses UV-C light and ozone technology to interrupt the growth process. UV-C damages microbial DNA and prevents bacteria from reproducing. Ozone helps destroy cell structures. Together, they eliminate 99.9% of bacteria, viruses, and fungi in just 3–5 minutes. Since the process is dry, it does not add moisture that could encourage new growth. This breaks the cycle and keeps helmets hygienic.\\\"},\\\"cta-contact\\\":{\\\"type\\\":\\\"cta\\\",\\\"heading\\\":\\\"Take Control of Helmet Hygiene\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"Now that you understand the science behind bacterial growth, it’s clear why proper sanitization is important. Keep your helmet clean and protect your health.\\\",\\\"label\\\":\\\"Learn More About FreshPod\\\",\\\"href\\\":\\\"/#contact\\\"}},\\\"seo\\\":{\\\"metaTitle\\\":\\\"The Science Behind Helmet Bacteria Growth Explained\\\",\\\"metaDescription\\\":\\\"Learn how sweat, heat, moisture, and nutrients cause rapid bacterial and fungal growth inside motorcycle helmets, and how proper sanitization prevents it.\\\",\\\"keywords\\\":[\\\"helmet bacteria growth\\\",\\\"bacteria multiplication helmet\\\",\\\"microbial growth helmet\\\",\\\"sweat bacteria science\\\",\\\"helmet fungi growth\\\",\\\"temperature humidity helmet germs\\\",\\\"helmet hygiene\\\",\\\"bacteria growth science\\\"],\\\"ogImage\\\":\\\"/images/banners/helmet-bacteria-science.jpg\\\",\\\"canonicalUrl\\\":\\\"https://freshpod.in/blog/the-science-behind-helmet-bacteria-growth\\\",\\\"schemaType\\\":\\\"BlogPosting\\\",\\\"aeo\\\":{\\\"faqItems\\\":[{\\\"q\\\":\\\"What temperature allows bacteria to grow fastest in helmets?\\\",\\\"a\\\":\\\"Most common helmet bacteria grow best between 25–40°C, which matches the internal temperature of helmets during rides in warm climates.\\\"},{\\\"q\\\":\\\"Why does sweat increase bacterial growth?\\\",\\\"a\\\":\\\"Sweat provides moisture and nutrients such as proteins and salts, creating ideal conditions for bacteria and fungi to multiply.\\\"},{\\\"q\\\":\\\"How can bacterial growth inside helmets be stopped?\\\",\\\"a\\\":\\\"Using dry disinfection methods such as UV-C and ozone helps eliminate microbes without adding moisture, preventing further growth.\\\"}]},\\\"geo\\\":{\\\"locality\\\":\\\"India\\\",\\\"region\\\":\\\"Andhra Pradesh\\\",\\\"country\\\":\\\"India\\\"}}}}]]\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"19:[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"meta\\\",\\\"0\\\",{\\\"charSet\\\":\\\"utf-8\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"meta\\\",\\\"1\\\",{\\\"name\\\":\\\"viewport\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\\\"}]]\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"1e:I[27201,[\\\"/_next/static/chunks/ff1a16fafef87110.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/d2be314c3ece3fbe.js\\\"],\\\"IconMark\\\"]\\n17:null\\n\"])</script><script